<br>
The Reuben James was doing convoy duty for US flag vessels.  Prior to that, the Germans declared unlimited sinking of vessels across the Atlantic.  US vessels were sunk in broad daylight in view of swimmers on beaches along the east coast. Sure FDR knew we had to kick the manufacturers up to get us finally out of the Great Depression, he knew that we were going to war, like it or not.<br>
<br>
If you want to point your finger at German supporters, don't limit it to Democrats.  Henry Ford used to have a portrait of Hitler hanging in his office. Lindberg may not have been a German supporter.  Some sources place him as spying for the US government on an informal basis. Letting his contacts in Germany unwittingly help us to obtain information.<br>
<br>
Politics also had alot to do with the emphasis on one theater or another.  Agreements at Oran and prior gave little leeway to where resources were sent.  Russia was putting a lot of pressure for a second front to be opened.  <br>
<br>
The Japanese army and naval forces did not have the resources to do more than possibly, only possibly invade the Hawaiian Islands.  Their invasion of the Aleutians was only  a side show that they weren't prepared to expand upon.  Most of their armed forces were deeply involved with operations in China and Burma. Once our newer fleet submarines made their appearance vulnerable Japanese shipping was damaged soundly.  The Japanese didn't have the resources that we had.  FDR cut them off from our scrap metal supplies which hurt their heavy industry prior to Pearl Harbor. By hemming them in and cutting off supplies of raw materials we had already stopped their military potential. <br>
<br>
The earlier Japanese attacks were well planned and executed.  In Jungle warfare the Australian troops showed to be at least their equals if not better in performance.  There were not the layed out jungle trails and paths in New Guinea as there was in Malaysia. When a Japanese Division tried to cross the mountains there, it wasn't Allied troops that stopped them as much as it was the jungle itself.  The jungle ripped them to less than half strength. In Guadalcanal as wel,l the jungle was our ally as much as it was our enemy.<br>
<br>
Nobody can justify the barbaric treatment that the Japanese gave to all prisoners that they captured.  Including what they did to the Chinese civilians, Medical testing and all.<br>
<br>
You should read &quot;Foo&quot; the memoirs of Frank Fujita.  He was a member an artillery battalion of the Texas Division that went to Java and was captured there spending the rest of the war as a POW.  Frank was half Japanese, the Japanese wanted to use him for propaganda purposes. You should read it. <br>
<br>
One last thing, I lived through Jimmie Carter.  He was too much of a hands-on leader and should have delegated more. He did cut off the Soviet Union from supplies of US microchips. When a MiG 25 landed in Japan with a defecting pilot it was found that all the microchips on board were products of Texas Instruments.  Most of the other electronics was based upon vacuum tubes.  People laughed at Jimmie Carter for doing that embargo.  The hostage situation with Iran was a troublesome affair.  Iran was probably weakening Carter's position by secretly talking to Reagan.<br>
<br>
I can go on and on with this.  There are multiple views on all these subjects and these are mine based upon what I have read and lived through. Good books to read are any by Carlo d'Este about the European Theater. <br>
