<br>
(sidebar: I don't believe the jungle could have been much of an ally to the U.S. According to one Japanese officer interviewed, we never fought in the jungle. We blew the jungle away and fought in the craters (as God intended <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ))<br>
<br>
Actually, let's stop wasting time.<br>
<br>
WWII was started as a secret plot by the U.S. to get the rest of the world fighting. Pearl Harbor wasn't actually attacked by the Japanese; they sent a friendship delegation fleet to discuss terms for mutually beneficial relations, and we ambushed them unexpectedly. Being arrogant and overbearing as all Americans have always been since 1492, we underestimated the resolve of their security guards who responded with pepperspray. We then blew up our own fleet to start the war.<br>
And, of course, the real scandal of the war in Europe is that it took so long. The German army actually only employed 8 footsoldiers equipped with clubs and rocks, while the U.S. attacked them mercilessly with nuclear powered battle tanks (known as &quot;Bolos&quot; I believe) and our supersonic aircraft flew mission after mission shooting down their entire air force of 18 unarmed hot-air balloons. The V1 and V2 rockets were a myth we created to hide the secret R&amp;D project we had going at area 51 as a delivery system for our nuclear bombs, which we were going to rain down on Mars as soon as we'd whipped the Germans and Japanese. that's why the Viking probes showed Mars to be a dead landscape even though Schiappereli had shown at the turn of the century that they had a high culture there including an extensive canal system.<br>
<br>
The death camps, however, really were death camps. That's where the Germans had their elite forces armed with machine guns and nightvision goggles to ensure that none of the suffering victims overpowered their guards and escaped. Of course, there were thousands of attemps, most of which were successful in spite of the prisoners being half-starved and unarmed. Here in the U.S. in the concentration camps, none of the 322 million prisoners even tried to escape, because they were all staked out on anthills for 4 years. In fact, the last two escaped just last week. In CNN interview one of them related how he'd been forced to witness the execution by beheading of 48 million prisoners who tried to escape by asking a guard, &quot;The war's been over 40 years, can we go home now, pleeeease?&quot;<br>
<br>
Revisionist history is fun.<br>
<br>
As for Jimmy Carter, that ain't history, that's personal. He was too hands-on because he was a f-ing incompetent balless wonder. He <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> emasculated</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> my country. I'd kiss &quot;Jihad&quot; Johnny Walker's poop-covered butt if it meant Carter were to be tried for treason in his place. &quot;We'll have to just get used to being just another country&quot;... &quot;We'll have to tighten our belts&quot;... &quot;The future will be darker than it has been&quot;. &quot;We live in a world of limited resources. &quot; (How limited can a world 15 billion lightyears across be???) Screw Russians getting microchips. He didn't stop the damned Japanese invasion. He read the fallacious Club of Rome reports and believed it as if he were a Branch Davidian at Waco. <br>
